6
7 An Act relating to pharmacy benefits managers;
amending 59 O.S. 2021, Sections 357, as last amended
8 by Section 2, Chapter 414, O.S.L. 2025, and 360, as
last amended by Section 8, Chapter 300, O.S.L. 2025
9 (59 O.S. Supp. 2025, Sections 357 and 360), which
relate to definitions and pharmacy benefits manager
10 contractual duties to provider; defining term;
prohibiting pharmacy benefits manager from refusing
11 to accept certain documentation; requiring certain
adjusted reimbursement amount if certain appeal is
12 approved; allowing certain provider to request
certain reversal or rebilling; requiring certain
13 information to be included in certain appeal;
requiring certain adjustments to include certain
14 claim-level details within certain time period;
prohibiting certain reimbursement amounts; updating
15 statutory references; updating statutory language;
and providing an effective date.
16
17
18 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
19 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 59 O.S. 2021, Section 357, as last
20 amended by Section 2, Chapter 414, O.S.L. 2025 (59 O.S. Supp. 2025,
21 Section 357), is amended to read as follows:
22 Section 357. A. As used in Sections 357 through 360 360.1 of
23 this title:
24
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3538 Page 1

1 1. "Acquisition cost" means the total amount paid by a provider
2 to acquire a drug, medical product, or device at the time of
3 purchase as evidenced by verifiable purchase documentation such as
4 an invoice or electronic price file. Acquisition cost shall include
5 purchase price, procurement fees, and associated shipping or
6 handling charges and shall not include any post-purchase rebates,
7 discounts, or credits that are not guaranteed and applied at the
8 time of sale;
9 2. "Covered entity" means a nonprofit hospital or medical
10 service organization, for-profit hospital or medical service
11 organization, insurer, health benefit plan, health maintenance
12 organization, health program administered by the state in the
13 capacity of providing health coverage, or an employer, labor union,
14 or other group of persons that provides health coverage to persons
15 in this state. This term does not include a health benefit plan
16 that provides coverage only for accidental injury, specified
17 disease, hospital indemnity, disability income, or other limited
18 benefit health insurance policies and contracts that do not include
19 prescription drug coverage;
20 2. 3. "Covered individual" means a member, participant,
21 enrollee, contract holder or policy holder or beneficiary of a
22 covered entity who is provided health coverage by the covered
23 entity. A covered individual includes any dependent or other person
24
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3538 Page 2

1 prov ided health coverage through a policy, contract or plan for a
2 covered individual;
3 3. 4. "Department" means the Insurance Department;
4 4. 5. "Effective rate contracting" means any agreement or
5 arrangement between a pharmacy or contracting agent acting on behalf
6 of a pharmacy and a pharmacy benefits manager for pharmaceuticals
7 based on the effective rate of payment rather than a predetermined
8 fixed price or fixed discount percentage;
9 5. 6. "Maximum allowable cost", "MAC", or "MAC list" means the
10 list of drug products delineating the maximum per-unit reimbursement
11 for multiple-source prescription drugs, medical product products, or
12 device devices;
13 6. 7. "Multisource drug product reimbursement" (reimbursement)
14 means the total amount paid to a pharmacy inclusive of any reduction
15 in payment to the pharmacy, excluding prescription dispense fees and
16 professional fees;
17 7. 8. "Office" means the Office of the Attorney General;
18 8. 9. "Pharmacy benefits management" means a service provided
19 to covered entities to facilitate the provision of prescription drug
20 benefits to covered individuals within the state, including
21 negotiating pricing and other terms with drug manufacturers and
22 providers. Pharmacy benefits management may include any or all of
23 the following services:
24
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3538 Page 3

1 a. claims processing, retail network management and
2 payment of claims to pharmacies for prescription drugs
3 dispensed to covered individuals,
4 b. clinical formulary development and management
5 services, or
6 c. rebate contracting and administration;
7 9. 10. "Pharmacy benefits manager" or "PBM" means a person,
8 business, or other entity that performs pharmacy benefits
9 management. The term shall include a person or entity acting on
10 behalf of a PBM in a contractual or employment relationship in the
11 performance of pharmacy benefits management for a managed care
12 company, nonprofit hospital, medical service organization, insurance
13 company, third-party payor, or a health program administered by an
14 agency or department of this state;
15 10. 11. "Plan sponsor" means the employers, insurance
16 companies, unions and health maintenance organizations or any other
17 entity responsible for establishing, maintaining, or administering a
18 health benefit plan on behalf of covered individuals; and
19 11. 12. "Provider" means a pharmacy licensed by the State Board
20 of Pharmacy, or an agent or representative of a pharmacy, including,
21 but not limited to, the pharmacy's contracting agent, which
22 dispenses prescription drugs or devices to covered individuals.
23 B. Nothing in the definition of pharmacy benefits management or
24 pharmacy benefits manager in the Patient's Right to Pharmacy Choice
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3538 Page 4

1 Act, Pharmacy Audit Integrity Act, or Sections 357 through 360 360.1
2 of this title shall deem an employer a "pharmacy benefits manager"
3 of its own self-funded health benefit plan, except, to the extent
4 permitted by applicable law, where the employer, without the
5 utilization of a third party and unrelated to the employer's own
6 pharmacy:
7 a. negotiates,
8 1. Negotiates directly with drug manufacturers;
9 b. processes,
10 2. Processes claims on behalf of its members; or
11 c. manages
12 3. Manages its own retail network of pharmacies.
13 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 59 O.S. 2021, Section 360, as last
14 amended by Section 8, Chapter 300, O.S.L. 2025 (59 O.S. Supp. 2025,
15 Section 360), is amended to read as follows:
16 Section 360. A. The pharmacy benefits manager (PBM) shall,
17 with respect to contracts between a pharmacy benefits manager and a
18 provider, including a pharmacy service administrative organization:
19 l. Include in such contracts the specific sources utilized to
20 determine the maximum allowable cost (MAC) pricing of the pharmacy,
21 update MAC pricing at least every seven (7) calendar days, and
22 establish a process for providers to readily access the MAC list
23 specific to that provider;
24
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3538 Page 5

1 2. In order to place a drug on the MAC list, ensure that the
2 drug is listed as "A" or "B" rated in the most recent version of the
3 United States Food and Drug Administration (FDA) Approved Drug
4 Products with Therapeutic Equivalence Evaluations, also known as the
5 Orange Book, and the drug is generally available for purchase by
6 pharmacies in the state from national or regional wholesalers and is
7 not obsolete;
8 3. Ensure dispensing fees are not included in the calculation
9 of MAC price reimbursement to pharmacy providers;
10 4. Provide a reasonable administration appeals procedure to
11 allow a provider, a provider's representative and a pharmacy service
12 administrative organization to contest reimbursement amounts within
13 fourteen (14) calendar days of the final adjusted payment date. The
14 pharmacy benefits manager shall not prevent the pharmacy or the
15 pharmacy service administrative organization from filing
16 reimbursement appeals in an electronic batch format. The pharmacy
17 benefits manager must PBM shall respond to a provider, a provider's
18 representative and a pharmacy service administrative organization
19 who have contested a reimbursement amount through this procedure
20 within ten (10) calendar days. The pharmacy benefits manager must
21 PBM shall respond in an electronic batch format to reimbursement
22 appeals filed in an electronic batch format. The pharmacy benefits
23 manager PBM shall not require a pharmacy or pharmacy services
24 administrative organization to log into a system to upload
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3538 Page 6

1 indi vidual claim appeals or to download individual appeal responses.
2 A PBM shall not refuse to accept additional documentation from
3 providers after submission of the appeal. If a price update is
4 warranted, the pharmacy benefits manager PBM shall make the change
5 in the reimbursement amount, permit the dispensing pharmacy to
6 reverse and rebill the claim in question, and make the reimbursement
7 amount change retroactive and effective for all contracted
8 providers;
9 5. If a below-cost reimbursement appeal is denied, the PBM
10 shall provide the reason for the denial, including the National Drug
11 Code (NDC) number from, and the name of, the specific national or
12 regional wholesalers doing business in this state where the drug is
13 currently in stock and available for purchase by the dispensing
14 pharmacy at a price below the PBM's reimbursement price. The PBM
15 shall include documented proof from the specific national or
16 regional wholesalers doing business in this state showing that the
17 drug is currently in stock and available for purchase by the
18 dispensing pharmacy at a price below the PBM's reimbursement price.;
19 6. If the NDC number provided by the pharmacy benefits manager
20 PBM is not available below the acquisition cost obtained from the
21 pharmaceutical wholesaler from whom the dispensing pharmacy
22 purchases the majority of the prescription drugs that are dispensed,
23 the pharmacy benefits manager PBM shall immediately adjust the
24 reimbursement amount, permit the dispensing pharmacy to reverse and
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3538 Page 7

1 rebi ll the claim in question, and make the reimbursement amount
2 adjustment retroactive and effective for all contracted providers
3 effective for all prescriptions of the appealed drug, medical
4 product, or device for patients covered under the same Bank
5 Identification Number (BIN) and Processor Control Number (PCN),
6 retroactive to the date of service of the initially appealed claim.
7 A PBM shall notify the provider that an increase has been granted
8 because of a reimbursement appeal. If a claim subject to an
9 approved appeal is not reversed and reprocessed within thirty (30)
10 calendar days after the final appeal determination, the PBM shall
11 remit to the provider the full reimbursement amount required by the
12 approved appeal, including any retroactive adjustments, and shall
13 not require the provider to refund or otherwise return any portion
14 of the reimbursement paid for that claim;
15 6. 7. Any appeal that results in an increase in the
16 reimbursement from the PBM that continues to be below the pharmacy's
17 acquisition cost shall be considered a denial under this section.
18 Any denial of an appeal shall follow the requirements of paragraph
19 paragraphs 5 and 6 of this subsection; and
20 7. 8. The PBM shall not require a pharmacy to collect
21 additional monies following a successful below-cost reimbursement
22 appeal from any person or entity other than the PBM who adjudicated
23 the drug claim, including the patient or plan sponsor; and
24
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3538 Page 8

1 9. Any adjustment to provider reimbursement shall be
2 accompanied by complete claim-level detail sufficient to reconcile
3 the adjustment, including identification of the original claim
4 payment values and the revised values for all affected fields. An
5 adjustment for which such claim-level detail is not provided
6 contemporaneously shall be deemed incomplete.
7 B. The reimbursement appeal requirements in this section shall
8 apply to all drugs, medical products, or devices reimbursed
9 according to any payment methodology, including, but not limited to:
10 1. Average acquisition cost, including the National Average
11 Drug Acquisition Cost;
12 2. Average manufacturer price;
13 3. Average wholesale price;
14 4. Brand effective rate or generic effective rate;
15 5. Discount indexing;
16 6. Federal upper limits;
17 7. Wholesale acquisition cost; and
18 8. Any other term that a pharmacy benefits manager PBM or an
19 insurer of a health benefit plan may use to establish reimbursement
20 rates to a pharmacist or pharmacy for pharmacist services.
21 C. The pharmacy benefits manager PBM shall not place a drug on
22 a MAC list, unless there are at least two therapeutically
23 equivalent, multiple-source drugs, generally available for purchase
24
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3538 Page 9

1 by d ispensing retail pharmacies from national or regional
2 wholesalers.
3 D. In the event that a drug is placed on the FDA Drug Shortages
4 Database, pharmacy benefits managers PBMs shall reimburse claims to
5 pharmacies at no less than the wholesale acquisition cost for the
6 specific NDC number being dispensed.
7 E. The pharmacy benefits manager PBM shall not require
8 accreditation or licensing of providers, or any entity licensed or
9 regulated by the State Board of Pharmacy, other than by the State
10 Board of Pharmacy or federal government entity as a condition for
11 participation as a network provider.
12 F. A pharmacy or pharmacist may decline to provide the
13 pharmacist clinical or dispensing services to a patient or pharmacy
14 benefits manager if the pharmacy or pharmacist is to be paid less
15 than the pharmacy's cost for providing the pharmacist clinical or
16 dispensing services.
17 G. The pharmacy benefits manager PBM shall provide a dedicated
18 telephone number, email address and names of the personnel with
19 decision-making authority regarding MAC appeals and pricing.
20 H. A PBM shall not reimburse a provider for a prescription drug
21 or pharmacy service in an amount less than the national average drug
22 acquisition cost for the prescription drug or pharmacy service at
23 the time the drug is administered or dispensed, plus a professional
24 dispensing fee of no less than the Medicaid fee-for-service
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3538 Page 10

1 prof essional dispensing fee rate established under rules promulgated
2 by the Oklahoma Health Care Authority Board. If the national
3 average drug acquisition cost is not available at the time a drug is
4 administered or dispensed, a PBM shall not reimburse in an amount
5 that is less than the wholesale acquisition cost of the drug
6 pursuant to 42 U.S.C., Section 1395w-3a(c)(6)(B), and shall
7 reimburse a professional dispensing fee of no less than the rate
8 established by the Board. The dispensing fee shall be evaluated
9 every two (2) years and shall be adjusted for inflation in even-
10 numbered years beginning November 1, 2026.
11 SECTION 3. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
12 Passed the House of Representatives the 25th day of March, 2026.
